An '''Administrative Monetary Penalty''' is a [[civil penalty]] imposed by a regulator for a contravention of an Act, regulation or by-law.{{sfn|LCO|2011|p=50}} It is issued upon discovery of an unlawful event, and is due and payable subject only to any rights of review that may be available under the AMP's implementing scheme.{{sfn|LCO|2011|p=50}} It is regulatory in nature, rather than criminal, and is intended to secure compliance with a regulatory scheme,{{sfn|LCO|2011|p=50}} and it can be employed with the use of other administrative sanctions, such as [[demerit point]]s and [[administrative license suspension|license suspension]]s.{{sfn|AG Ontario|2015|p=2}}

==Nature==
AMPs differ from ordinary fines, such as those for [[parking ticket]]s, in that, under the relevant legislation:{{sfn|AG BC|2008|p=5}}

#the AMP applies to a narrower segment of the general population (for example, a regulated industry);   
#imposing an AMP involves a number of steps, for instance, the person may first be given a warning and/or an opportunity to address the statutory decision-maker’s concerns (that is, to comply with the scheme); 
#the decision to impose an AMP is made by a senior official such as a Director or a person designated by that Director; 
#the criteria to guide the determination whether to impose and how to set the amount of an AMP is set out; 
#within those criteria, the person empowered to levy the penalty may be given significant discretion to decide whether to impose an AMP and to determine the appropriate amount of the AMP; and   
#the reconsideration or review/appeal of an AMP by the statutory decision-maker and/or an independent, specialized tribunalis allowed.

==AMPs by jurisdiction==
===United Kingdom===
Legislation enabling general schemes of fixed and variable monetary penalties{{em dash}}in addition to other sanctions{{em dash}}has been introduced through Part 3 of the ''[[Regulatory Enforcement and Sanctions Act 2008]]''.{{sfn|Prabhu|2011|pp=130{{en dash}}132}}

Under the ''Road Traffic Act 1991''{{em dash}}and subsequently expanded under part 6 of the ''[[Traffic Management Act 2004]]''{{em dash}}AMPs known as "penalty charge notices" have replaced [[fixed penalty notice]]s where local authorities have adopted schemes of [[decriminalised parking enforcement]]. In some areas such as [[London, England|London]], the challenge process for PCNs can be completed online, via the Internet.<ref>{{cite web|title=Environment and Traffic Adjudicators|url=http://www.londontribunals.gov.uk/eat|publisher=[[London Tribunals]]|accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref>

===Canada===
In ''[[Guindon v Canada]]'',<ref>{{cite CanLII|litigants=Guindon v Canada|link=Guindon v Canada|year=2015|court=scc|num=41}}</ref> the [[Supreme Court of Canada]] ruled that AMPs are generally considered to be administrative in nature and thus not subject to the legal protections provided under [[Section 11 of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms|s.11]] of the ''[[Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms]]''. They are held not to arise from criminal proceedings, as "the purpose ... is to promote honesty and deter gross negligence"<ref>''Guindon'', par. 62</ref> and "it is rational that the state would only wish to impose a penalty on those who engage in misconduct knowingly, recklessly, or with a particular intention."<ref>''Guindon'', par. 72</ref> They also do not attract a true penal consequence, as "high administrative monetary penalties [are] required to encourage compliance with the administrative regime. The relevant question is not the amount of the penalty in absolute terms, it is whether the amount serves regulatory rather than penal purposes."<ref>''Guindon'', par. 81</ref>

However, normal standards of [[judicial review]] continue to apply.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.administrativelawmatters.com/blog/2015/08/03/its-just-a-fine-guindon-v-canada-2015-scc-41/|title= It’s Just (a) Fine: ''Guindon v. Canada'', 2015 SCC 41|last1= Daly|first1= Paul |date= August 3, 2015|website= administrativelawmatters.com|publisher= }}</ref> In ''Guindon'', the [[Federal Court of Appeal (Canada)|Federal Court of Appeal]] provided more guidance in its judgment as to when an administrative penalty would be considered disproportionate.<ref>{{cite CanLII|litigants=Canada v Guindon|year=2013|court=fca|num=153|pinpoint=par. 44|date=2013-06-12}}</ref> The [[Ontario Court of Appeal]] has given a reasoned evaluation for a monetary penalty that arose from a securities proceeding,<ref>{{cite CanLII|litigants=Rowan v. Ontario Securities Commission|link=|year=2012|court=onca|num=208|pinpoint=par. 52, 55|parallelcite=110 OR (3d) 492|date=2012-03-29}}</ref> and the [[Administrative Tribunal of Quebec]] has recognized that a person can bring forward the "reasonable, prudent and diligent person" defence that exists in civil law against the imposition of AMPs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canadianenergylawblog.com/2015/08/04/supreme_court_of_canada_upholds_the_constitutional_validity_of_administrative_monetary_penalties/ |title=Supreme Court of Canada upholds the constitutional validity of administrative monetary penalties |last1=Gagné |first1=Michel |last2=Frémont |first2=Catherine |date=August 4, 2015 |website=canadianenergylawblog.com |publisher=[[McCarthy Tétrault]] |access-date= |quote= }}, citing ''Excavation René St-Pierre Inc. c Québec'', [http://www.canlii.org/fr/qc/qctaq/doc/2015/2015canlii7296/2015canlii7296.html 2015 QCTAQ 02386]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>

The [[Government of Canada]] has introduced various AMP schemes on a sector-by-sector basis,<ref>including the ''[[Aeronautics Act]]'', the ''Customs Act'', the ''Income Tax Act'', the ''Employment Insurance Act'' and the 
''Agriculture and Agri-Food Administrative Monetary Penalties Act</ref> although some agencies prefer to pursue ticketing schemes for specified [[summary offence]]s, notably under the ''[[Contraventions Act]]''.{{sfn|Prabhu|2011|pp=139{{en dash}}140}}

[[Ontario]] is considering creating a new AMP system to address minor offences that are currently prosecuted under its ''Provincial Offences Act''. The [[Attorney General of Ontario]] has requested input into the new system being proposed.{{sfn|AG Ontario|2015|p=1}} In response, some have suggested that, with proper planning, an online system would be more cost-efficient and promote easier access to justice for people in rural areas and for those with language barriers.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chatten|first1=David|title=Online AMP System - A Strong Move for Ontario|url=https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/administrative-monetary-penalties-great-move-ontario-david-chatten|accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref> However, some people fear that a new system will be cumbersome and will not allow access to justice.<ref>{{cite web|title=Driving Down Business|url=http://paralegalscope.com/driving-down-business-province-rolls-out-diy-online-poa-challenges/|website=Paralegal Scope Magazine|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref>

