{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}
{{short description|French sculptor, medallist and painter}}
[[File:Signature Elisa Beetz.JPG|thumb|Signature of Elisa Beetz]]
'''Élisa Beetz-Charpentier''' (born '''Jeanne Élisa Henriette Beetz'''<ref name="Geni">[https://www.geni.com/people/Jeanne-%C3%89lisa-Beetz/6000000067809854856 Jeanne Élisa Henriette Beetz] – [[Geni.com]]</ref>; 1859 in [[Schaerbeek]], Belgium – 1949 in [[Neuilly-sur-Seine]], France)<ref name="Orsay">[http://www.musee-orsay.fr/fr/espace-professionnels/professionnels/chercheurs/rech-rec-art-home/notice-artiste.html?nnumid=2686 ''Elisa Beetz-Charpentier''.] In: [[Musée d’Orsay]]</ref> was a French sculptor, [[medallist]] and painter.

Her second husband was [[Alexandre Charpentier]] and the witnesses at their wedding in 1908 were [[Claude Debussy]] and [[Auguste Rodin]].<ref>Jana Wijnsouw: [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=THE3DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT393 ''National Identity and Nineteenth-Century Franco-Belgian Sculpture.''] Routledge, 2017, {{ISBN|1-35177-814-5}}, S.&nbsp;393.</ref>

According to the research of Polish [[heraldist]] Jerzy Michta published in 2017, the version of the [[coat of arms of Poland]] used since 1927, designed by artist Zygmunt Kamiński, was actually plagiarized from a 1924 plaque by Elisa Beetz-Charpentier made in honor of [[Ignacy Paderewski]].<ref name="RP">Wiktor Ferfecki: [https://www.rp.pl/Historia/310289962-Godlo-Polski-jest-plagiatem.html Godło Polski jest plagiatem?]. [[Rzeczpospolita (newspaper)|Rzeczpospolita]], 29 October 2018.</ref> 

